  "prompt": "What is a good way to track the K-factor in Google Analytics?",
  "response": "To track the K-factor (viral coefficient) in Google Analytics, you can use several methods:\n\n1. Custom Event Tracking\n- Set up custom events when users share or refer\n- Track referral sources and number of new users generated\n- Use Google Analytics event tracking code\n\n2. Campaign Tagging\n- Create unique UTM parameters for viral sharing links\n- Use Google's Campaign URL Builder\n- Track specific referral sources and conversion paths\n\n3. Custom Dimensions\n- Create custom dimensions for referral tracking\n- Capture referrer information and viral spread\n\n4. Goal Tracking\n- Set up goals for viral actions\n- Track conversions from referrals\n- Monitor referral conversion rates\n\n5. Advanced Techniques\n- Use Google Analytics Enhanced Ecommerce\n- Implement user ID tracking\n- Utilize Google Tag Manager for complex tracking\n\n6. Third-Party Tools\n- Amplitude\n- Mixpanel\n- Google Analytics 4 (more advanced tracking)\n\nRecommended Implementation Steps:\n- Define viral actions\n- Create tracking mechanisms\n- Set up proper event/goal tracking\n- Analyze referral data regularly\n- Calculate K-factor manually or through analytics\n\nEach method has pros and cons, so choose based on your specific viral marketing strategy and technical capabilities.",
